      "earlier example with `n = 1` actually does not contradict the theorem because the terms are not as we thought. For `n = 1`, there is only `i = j = 0`, so:\n`‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x i - x j| = ‚ąö|x 0 - x 0| = 0`,\n`‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x i + x j| = ‚ąö|x 0 + x 0| = ‚ąö|2x 0|`. The inequality is `0 ‚Č§ ‚ąö|2x 0|`, which is always true.\n\nSimilarly, for `n = 2`, take `x 0 = 1`, `x 1 = -1`:\n`‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x i - x j| = ‚ąö|1 - 1| + ‚ąö|1 - (-1)| + ‚ąö|-1 - 1| + ‚ąö|-1 - (-1)| = 0 + ‚ąö2 + ‚ąö2 + 0 = 2‚ąö2`.\n`‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x i + x j| = ‚ąö|1 + 1| + ‚ąö|1 + (-1)| + ‚ąö|-1 + 1| + ‚ąö|-1 + (-1)| = ‚ąö2 + 0 + 0 + ‚ąö2 = 2‚ąö2`.\nSo, `2‚ąö2 ‚Č§ 2‚ąö2` is true.\n\nWait, perhaps my earlier \"counterexample\" was incorrect because I was not summing over all pairs but considering just one pair. Let me re-examine the original problem.\n\n#### Correct Approach:\nThe theorem is actually correct as stated, because for each pair `(i, j)`, we cannot guarantee that `‚ąö|x_i - x_j| ‚Č§ ‚ąö|x_i + x_j|`, but the sum over all pairs satisfies the inequality. \n\nBut why? \n\nLet me try more examples.\n\n**Example 1:**\n`n = 2`, `x 0 = 1`, `x 1 = 0`.\n`‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x i - x j| = ‚ąö1 + ‚ąö1 + ‚ąö0 + ‚ąö1 = 1 + 1 + 0 + 1 = 3`.\n`‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x i + x j| = ‚ąö2 + ‚ąö1 + ‚ąö1 + ‚ąö0 ‚Čą 1.414 + 1 + 1 + 0 ‚Čą 3.414`.\nHere, `3 ‚Č§ 3.414`.\n\n**Example 2:**\n`n = 2`, `x 0 = 1`, `x 1 = 1`.\n`‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x i - x j| = 0 + 0 + 0 + 0 = 0`.\n`‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x i + x j| = ‚ąö2 + ‚ąö2 + ‚ąö2 + ‚ąö2 ‚Čą 5.656`.\n`0 ‚Č§ 5.656`.\n\n**Example 3:**\n`n = 2`, `x 0 = 1`, `x 1 = -2`.\n`‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x i - x j| = ‚ąö3 + ‚ąö3 + ‚ąö3 + ‚ąö3 = 4‚ąö3 ‚Čą 6.928`.\n`‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x i + x j| = ‚ąö|1 + 1| + ‚ąö|-1| + ‚ąö|-1| + ‚ąö4 = ‚ąö2 + 1 + 1 + 2 ‚Čą 1.414 + 1 + 1 + 2 ‚Čą 5.414`.\nWait, here `4‚ąö3 ‚Čą 6.928 > 5.414`, so this contradicts the theorem!\n\nBut no, I made a mistake in computing the sums:\nFor `x 0 = 1`, `x 1 = -2`, the four pairs are:\n`(0, 0): ‚ąö|1 - 1| = 0`,\n`(0, 1): ‚ąö|1 - (-2)| = ‚ąö3`,\n`(1, 0): ‚ąö|-2 - 1| = ‚ąö3`,\n`(1, 1): ‚ąö|-2 - (-2)| = 0`.\nSo `‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x i - x j| = 0 + ‚ąö3 + ‚ąö3 + 0 = 2‚ąö3 ‚Čą 3.464`.\n\nNow, `‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x i + x j|`:\n`(0, 0): ‚ąö|1 + 1| = ‚ąö2`,\n`(0, 1): ‚ąö|1 + (-2)| = 1`,\n`(1, 0): ‚ąö|-2 + 1| = 1`,\n`(1, 1): ‚ąö|-2 + (-2)| = ‚ąö4 = 2`.\nSum: `‚ąö2 + 1 + 1 + 2 ‚Čą 1.414 + 1 + 1 + 2 ‚Čą 5.414`.\n\nNow, `2‚ąö3 ‚Čą 3.464 ‚Č§ 5.414`, so the inequality holds.\n\nEarlier, I thought `(0, 0)` gave `‚ąö|1 + 1|`, but actually for `(i, j)` in Lean, it is `x i + x j`, not `x i + x i` unless `i = j`. \n\nThus, perhaps the inequality is true after all.\n\n#### Trying to Prove It:\nWe need to show that for each pair `(i, j)`, `‚ąö|x_i - x_j| ‚Č§ ‚ąö|x_i + x_j|`, or find another way to compare the sums globally. \n\nBut as the first example with `a = 1`, `b = -1` shows, this is not true. However, perhaps when we sum over all pairs, the positive contributions of some pairs outweigh the negative ones.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can exploit symmetries in the sum, e.g., that `(i, j)` and `(j, i)` are both included. \n\nBut perhaps it's better to think differently: since square root is concave and increasing, maybe we can use some inequality like `‚ąöa + ‚ąöb ‚Č§ ‚ąö(2(a + b))`, but that seems not directly useful.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps consider squaring both sides, but that introduces cross-terms that are complicated.\n\nAnother idea: notice that `|x_i - x_j| ‚Č§ |x_i| + |x_j|`, and `|x_i + x_j| ‚Č• ||x_i| - |x_j||`, but I'm not sure how to use this yet.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps consider that for any real `a, b`, `(a - b)^2 ‚Č§ (a + b)^2 + 4 min(|a|, |b|)^2`. Not sure.\n\nThis approach doesn't seem straightforward, so perhaps we need a better strategy.\n\n#### A Better Insight:\nActually, for each pair `(i, j)`, `|x_i - x_j|^2 ‚Č§ 2(|x_i|^2 + |x_j|^2)` and `|x_i + x_j|^2 ‚Č§ 2(|x_i|^2 + |x_j|^2)`, but this doesn't directly compare them.\n\nAlternatively, note that:\n`(|x_i + x_j|)^2 - (|x_i - x_j|)^2 = 4 x_i x_j`.\n\nThis is useful! \n\nBut `4 x_i x_j` can be positive or negative. \n\nHowever, in the double sum over all `(i, j)`, when we consider `(i, j)` and `(j, i)`, we have:\n`[ (|x_i + x_j|)^2 - (|x_i - x_j|)^2 ] + [ (|x_j + x_i|)^2 - (|x_j - x_i|)^2 ] = 8 x_i x_j`.\n\nBut since `|x_i - x_j| = |x_j - x_i|`, the sum becomes:\n`2 [ (|x_i + x_j|)^2 - (|x_i - x_j|)^2 ] = 8 x_i x_j`.\n\nThus, ` (|x_i + x_j|)^2 - (|x_i - x_j|)^2 = 4 x_i x_j`.\n\nNow, summing over all pairs `(i, j)`:\n`‚ąĎ_{i,j} [ (|x_i + x_j|)^2 - (|x_i - x_j|)^2 ] = 4 ‚ąĎ_{i,j} x_i x_j`.\n\nBut `‚ąĎ_{i,j} x_i x_j = (‚ąĎ_i x_i)^2`, because it's the product of sums.\n\nThus, the LHS is `‚ąĎ_{i,j} (|x_i + x_j|)^2 - ‚ąĎ_{i,j} (|x_i - x_j|)^2 = 4 (‚ąĎ_i x_i)^2`.\n\nBut the RHS `4 (‚ąĎ_i x_i)^2` can be positive or negative, but it doesn't immediately help us compare the sums of square roots.\n\nHmm, perhaps this is not directly useful.\n\n#### Trying to Use Specific Cases:\nPerhaps for `n = 1` it is trivial, as shown earlier. \n\nFor `n = 2`, let‚Äôs denote:\n`S = ‚ąö|x‚āĀ - x‚āĀ| + ‚ąö|x‚āĀ - x‚āā| + ‚ąö|x‚āā - x‚āĀ| + ‚ąö|x‚āā - x‚āā| = 2 ‚ąö|x‚āĀ - x‚āā|`.\n`T = ‚ąö|x‚āĀ + x‚āĀ| + ‚ąö|x‚āĀ + x‚āā| + ‚ąö|x‚āā + x‚āĀ| + ‚ąö|x‚āā + x‚āā| = 2 ‚ąö|x‚āĀ + x‚āā| + ‚ąö|2x‚āĀ| + ‚ąö|2x‚āā|`.\n\nWe have `2 ‚ąö|x‚āĀ - x‚āā| ‚Č§ 2 ‚ąö|x‚āĀ + x‚āā| + ‚ąö|2x‚āĀ| + ‚ąö|2x‚āā|`.\n\nThis is not obviously true. \n\nBut in the earlier case with `x‚āĀ = 1`, `x‚āā = -2`, it was:\n`2‚ąö3 ‚Č§ 2 * 1 + ‚ąö2 + ‚ąö4 ‚Čą 2 + 1.414 + 2 ‚Čą 5.414`, and `2‚ąö3 ‚Čą 3.464 ‚Č§ 5.414`.\n\nAnother case: `x‚āĀ = 2`, `x‚āā = -1`:\n`S = 2‚ąö3 ‚Čą 3.464`.\n`T = 2‚ąö1 + ‚ąö4 + ‚ąö|-2| = 2 + 2 + ‚ąö2 ‚Čą 4 + 1.414 ‚Čą 5.414`.\nAgain `3.464 ‚Č§ 5.414`.\n\nAnother case: `x‚āĀ = 1`, `x‚āā = 0`:\n`S = 2",
      "\n   \\[\n   \\text{LHS} = 2\\sqrt{|a - b|}, \\quad \\text{RHS} = \\sqrt{|a + b|} + \\sqrt{|a + b|} + 2 \\cdot 0 = 2\\sqrt{|a + b|} + 0.\n   \\]\n   Wait no, actually for `n = 2`, the sum is over `i, j ‚ąą {1, 2}`, so there are 4 terms:\n   \\[\n   \\text{LHS} = \\sqrt{|a - a|} + \\sqrt{|a - b|} + \\sqrt{|b - a|} + \\sqrt{|b - b|} = 2\\sqrt{|a - b|},\n   \\]\n   and similarly:\n   \\[\n   \\text{RHS} = \\sqrt{|a + a|} + \\sqrt{|a + b|} + \\sqrt{|b + a|} + \\sqrt{|b + b|} = 2\\sqrt{|a + b|} + 2\\sqrt{|2a|}.\n   \\]\n   Hmm, no, that's not correct: for `n = 2`, `‚ąĎ i, ‚ąĎ j, ‚ąö|x_i + x_j|` is:\n   - `i = 1, j = 1`: `‚ąö|a + a| = ‚ąö|2a|`\n   - `i = 1, j = 2`: `‚ąö|a + b|`\n   - `i = 2, j = 1`: `‚ąö|b + a|`\n   - `i = 2, j = 2`: `‚ąö|b + b| = ‚ąö|2b|`\n   So:\n   \\[\n   \\text{RHS} = \\sqrt{|2a|} + 2\\sqrt{|a + b|} + \\sqrt{|2b|}.\n   \\]\n   And LHS is `2‚ąö|a - b|`, as before. \n\n   So the inequality becomes:\n   \\[\n   2\\sqrt{|a - b|} \\leq \\sqrt{|2a|} + 2\\sqrt{|a + b|} + \\sqrt{|2b|}.\n   \\]\n   This looks plausible, because the RHS has more positive terms. For example, take `a = 1`, `b = -1`:\n   - LHS = `2‚ąö2 ‚Čą 2.828`\n   - RHS = `‚ąö2 + 2‚ąö0 + ‚ąö2 ‚Čą 1.414 + 0 + 1.414 ‚Čą 2.828`.\n   It holds as equality.\n   Take `a = 1`, `b = 1`:\n   - LHS = 0\n   - RHS = ‚ąö2 + 2‚ąö2 + ‚ąö2 ‚Čą 5.656.\n   It holds.\n   Take `a = 2`, `b = -1`:\n   - LHS = 2‚ąö3 ‚Čą 3.464\n   - RHS = ‚ąö4 + 2‚ąö1 + ‚ąö2 ‚Čą 2 + 2 + 1.414 ‚Čą 5.414.\n   It holds.\n\n   So perhaps for general `n`, the RHS has enough extra terms to compensate, even if individual pairs don't satisfy `‚ąö|a - b| ‚Č§ ‚ąö|a + b|`.\n\n   But this approach seems complicated because we have to consider all pairs. \n\n   Another idea: Perhaps we can write the sum as `‚ąĎ_{i,j} ‚ąö|x_i - x_j|` and note that for any fixed `i`, we have some relation when summing over `j`.\n\n   Alternatively, perhaps we can use the following fact: for any real numbers `a, b`, we have `‚ąö|a - b| ‚Č§ ‚ąö(|a| + |b|)` because `|a - b| ‚Č§ |a| + |b|`, and then try to compare `‚ąö(|a| + |b|)` with `‚ąö|a + b|`. But again, `|a| + |b| ‚Č• |a + b|`, so `‚ąö(|a| + |b|) ‚Č• ‚ąö|a + b|`, which gives the opposite of what we want. \n\n   Hmm, this approach doesn't work.\n\n   Maybe another approach: square both sides of the inequality? But the square of a sum is complicated. \n\n   Alternatively, perhaps consider that for any `i`, `‚ąĎ_j ‚ąö|x_i - x_j| ‚Č§ ‚ąĎ_j ‚ąö|x_i + x_j|`, and then sum over `i`. But as seen earlier, this isn't necessarily true for each `i`.\n\n   Alternatively, think about the following: \n   For any real numbers `a, b`, we have:\n   \\[\n   |a - b| ‚Č§ |a + b| + 2\\min(|a|, |b|).\n   \\]\n   For example:\n   - If `a, b ‚Č• 0`, then `|a - b| = |a + b| - 2b` if `a ‚Č• b`, or `-2a + |a + b|` if `a ‚Č§ b`. But `2\\min(a, b)` compensates appropriately.\n   - If `a = 1`, `b = -1`, then `|a - b| = 2`, `|a + b| = 0`, `2\\min(|a|, |b|) = 2`: `2 ‚Č§ 0 + 2`.\n   - If `a = 2`, `b = -1`, then `|a - b| = 3`, `|a + b| = 1`, `2\\min(2, 1) = 2`: `3 ‚Č§ 1 + 2`.\n   Hmm, this seems correct. \n\n   Hence, taking square roots:\n   \\[\n   \\sqrt{|a - b|} \\le",
